pwd = print working directory, shows where you are. 
ls = list directory
cd ../ = back up one directory
cd ../../ = back up further 
$HOME
clear = cleans the screen
cd (name of directory) = move to a directory
man ls = "manual list" gives you the operator's manual
    alternative lookup = google your command options (e.g. biostar)
q = quit, return to command line
ls -lrth = additional information 
head filename.fastq = prints 10 lines of the file to the screen
cat filename.fastq = prints the entire file to the screen
ls | grep 'something' = find everything in the folder with 'something'
cd ~ = brings you back to your home directory
**exam question: relative path = go straight to a directory (e.g. cd shellpath) vs absolute path = typing in the whole path. 
tab once = autocomplete
tab twice = gives you all the options
rm = delete the thing. can't get it back. 
rm -fR nameoffile = delete the folder and everything in it. 
git clone httplinkofgithubsitepastehere = clone git hub
up arrow = scroll through previous commands
history = prints history
grep 'thing' filename.fastq = search function to search for something within a file
    ^@ = search for the @ symbol at the beginning of a line
> filename.txt = saves the results as a txt file
ls *fastq = print anything that has the fastq ending
* = wildcard, sub anything into this spot. 
ls /bin = can search within the bin folder w/o being actually in that folder. 
wc = word count
wc -l = count the number of lines
ls /bin/ | grep '^c' | wc -l = find and count files that start with c


